Tom;<br>
Your insight is always thought provoking, it has always thrown me for a loop and a reexamination of what I believe. I love the challenge as it does help me to seek answers to questions I may not have thought about before and for that I thank you. <br>
There is I am sure you are aware of an e-mail signature to sites we visit and when we post to a site our signature is also noted, even when we do so anonymous. I seriously doubt that spatz has an impersonator out there. <br>
As a law enforcement officer, counselor and pastor I have had to deal with too many wackos out there who have said they are one thing and then reflect a different lifestyle. As former servicemen we tend to believe sometimes in a very naive way that others are honest in what they say, that is why, it burns me up to see individuals, like anymouse, spatz or others deceitfully use this means to degrade veterans for their own good pleasures. <br>
There are many scriptures that relate on how we ought to treat our enemy, but even Ester had to seek permission from her husband king before her people could defend themselves, before the wrong that would have surely wiped them out as a nation was executed. They prevailed by defending themselves and Israel survived.<br>
I've always tried to help others even at the expense of placing myself at the point of incoming fire; I have done no different here on this site. I hadn't noticed it as a trait in me, until I started posting here and realized what I was trying to do. Like a mother hen, guess I picked it up in Nam.<br>
But, Perhaps its also the failure of accomplishment in Nam, the sense of thing unaccomplished there, that has shadowed me all these years or its the desire for justice, and the believe in America and what is morally right that has always compelled me to challenge individuals like spatz, especially in the public arena. <br><br>
I remember one day as president of the local school board I was introducing Aid education for our High School students, I hated that it needed to be done, but youth awareness of its dangers overrode my desire that such things should not have to be addressed by public educators. I would much just have them teach, then to have to deal with drugs, gangs and other social ills. But during the introduction I made a statement that made the front page of the local newspaper the following day. It quoted me as saying, <br>
&quot;It's a shame that we have to introduce Aids education because of this disease, because a bunch of gay men went around playing with themselves.&quot;<br>
Of course by that afternoon many other local newspapers and a couple of television networks were interested in the story and were bombarding our districts administrators office with questions and or correction, it was evident that it was their desire was to crucify me. I responded by stating that I was misquoted. <br>
That the newspaper reporter had left out that I called it the &quot;deadly&quot; disease. My stand was therefore no longer newsworthy; I wasn't going to back down on what I believe. That is not to say that I don't when I am corrected, with five daughters I have had to seek shelter and call for a truce often.<br><br>
What is right is right, there is no problem in a good downy brook but if it escalates, there is no reason for us to back down. Yesterday one of my daughters was being recognized by the local American legion for having been our high schools girl state representative, she ran for city council and other positions while there and was elected, as were the two male students representing the other school in our area. A Vietnam veteran whose son was in the ROTC and who was providing security for us was just as proud of his son. But he said something that bothered me, he said, I'm am involved because I am old now, its over for us we've done our part now its our sons and daughters turn to take over. While I agreed with him about our sons and daughters I didn't agree with him as far as us as it being over for us Vietnam veterans, <br>
Tom we have too much to contribute yet to this world in need of understanding what Vietnam was all about. Sharing what we saw through the eyes of an eighteen, nineteen year old can awaken many others to the horrors of war as well as the need for commitment, honor and pride in what we accomplished, that made us what we are today and whose seeds are evident in our children.  <br><br>
If I have not said it before, I will now, Thank you Tom, thank you for being there in Nam and here now. But don't deny others the privilege of your wisdom because of the corrupt officials that govern the village. <br><br>
I too enjoy a good game of chess, learned it on the thirteen hour flight on my way back from Nan. <br>
In peace and war <br>
Cookie<br><br>

